# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: osquery-endpoint
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] The endpoint security space has evolved during the 2010s away from limited antivirus software and into a more advanced, comprehensive defense.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] This includes next-generation antivirus, threat detection, investigation, and response, device management, data leak protection (DLP), and other considerations to face evolving threats.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] Endpoint security management is a software approach that helps to identify and manage the users' computer and data access over a corporate network.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] This allows the network administrator to restrict the use of sensitive data as well as certain website access to specific users, to maintain, and comply with the organization's policies and standards.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] The components involved in aligning the endpoint security management systems include a virtual private network (VPN) client, an operating system and an updated endpoint agent.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] Computer devices that are not in compliance with the organization's policy are provisioned with limited access to a virtual LAN.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] Encrypting data on endpoints, and removable storage devices help to protect against data leaks.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] Endpoint security systems operate on a client-server model, with the security program controlled by a centrally managed host server pinned with a client program that is installed on all the network drives.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] There is another model called software as a service (SaaS), where the security programs and the host server are maintained remotely by the merchant.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] In the payment card industry, the contribution from both the delivery models is that the server program verifies and authenticates the user login credentials and performs a device scan to check if it complies with designated corporate security standards prior to permitting network access.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] In addition to protecting an organization's endpoints from potential threats, endpoint security allows IT admins to monitor operation functions and data backup strategies.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] An endpoint protection platform (EPP) is a solution deployed on endpoint devices to prevent file-based malware attacks, detect malicious activity, and provide the investigation and remediation capabilities needed to respond to dynamic security incidents and alerts.
[src:osquery-endpoint/endpoint-security] Several vendors, like Microsoft Defender, CrowdStrike, and Absolute Security, produce systems converging EPP systems with endpoint detection and response (EDR) platforms – systems focused on threat detection, response, and unified monitoring.
[src:osquery-endpoint/file-integrity-monitoring] Generally, the act of performing file integrity monitoring is automated using internal controls such as an application or process.
[src:osquery-endpoint/file-integrity-monitoring] Such monitoring can be performed randomly, at a defined polling interval, or in real-time.
[src:osquery-endpoint/file-integrity-monitoring] Changes to configurations, files and file attributes across the IT infrastructure are common, but hidden within a large volume of daily changes can be the few that impact file or configuration integrity.
[src:osquery-endpoint/file-integrity-monitoring] These changes can also reduce security posture and in some cases may be leading indicators of a breach in progress.
[src:osquery-endpoint/file-integrity-monitoring] Multiple compliance objectives indicate file integrity monitoring as a requirement.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] HIDS focuses on more granular and internal attacks through focusing monitoring host activities instead of overall network traffic.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] HIDS was the first type of intrusion detection software to have been designed, with the original target system being the mainframe computer where outside interaction was infrequent.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One major issue with using HIDS is that it needs to be installed on each and every computer that needs protection from intrusions.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] This can lead to a slowdown in device performance and intrusion detection systems.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A host-based IDS is capable of monitoring all or parts of the dynamic behavior and the state of a computer system, based on how it is configured.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Similarly a HIDS might look at the state of a system, its stored information, whether in RAM, in the file system, log files or elsewhere; and check that the contents of these appear as expected, e.g. have not been changed by intruders.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One can think of a HIDS as an agent that monitors whether anything or anyone, whether internal or external, has circumvented the system's security policy.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In comparison to network-based intrusion detection systems, HIDS is advantageous because of its capability of identifying internal attacks.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] While NIDS examines data from network traffic, HIDS examines data originating from operating systems.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In recent years, HIDS has been faced with the big data challenge, which can be attributed to the increased advancement of data center facilities and methodologies.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Many computer users have encountered tools that monitor dynamic system behavior in the form of anti-virus (AV) packages.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] While AV programs often also monitor system state, they do spend a lot of their time looking at who is doing what inside a computer – and whether a given program should or should not have access to particular system resources.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] The lines become blurred here, as many of the tools overlap in functionality.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Some intrusion prevention systems protect against buffer overflow attacks on system memory and can enforce security policy.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] The principle operation of a HIDS depends on the fact that successful intruders (hackers) will generally leave a trace of their activities.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In theory, a computer user has the ability to detect any such modifications, and the HIDS attempts to do just that and reports its findings.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Ideally a HIDS works in conjunction with a NIDS, such that a HIDS finds anything that slips past the NIDS.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Commercially available software solutions often do correlate the findings from NIDS and HIDS in order to find out about whether a network intruder has been successful or not at the targeted host.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Most successful intruders, on entering a target machine, immediately apply best-practice security techniques to secure the system which they have infiltrated, leaving only their own backdoor open, so that other intruders can not take over *their* computers.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In general a HIDS uses a database (object-database) of system objects it should monitor – usually (but not necessarily) file system objects.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS could also check that appropriate regions of memory have not been modified – for example, the system call table for Linux, and various vtable structures in Microsoft Windows.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] For each object in question a HIDS will usually remember its attributes (permissions, size, modifications dates) and create a checksum of some kind (an MD5, SHA1 hash or similar) for the contents, if any.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] This information gets stored in a secure database for later comparison (checksum database).
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] An alternate method to HIDS would be to provide NIDS type functionality at the network interface (NIC) level of an end-point (either server, workstation or other end device).
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Providing HIDS at the network layer has the advantage of providing more detailed logging of the source (IP address) of the attack and attack details, such as packet data, neither of which a dynamic behavioral monitoring approach could see.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] At installation time – and whenever any of the monitored objects change legitimately – a HIDS must initialize its checksum-database by scanning the relevant objects.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Persons in charge of computer security need to control this process tightly in order to prevent intruders making un-authorized changes to the database(s).
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Such initialization thus generally takes a long time and involves cryptographically locking each monitored object and the checksum databases or worse.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Because of this, manufacturers of HIDS usually construct the object-database in such a way that makes frequent updates to the checksum database unnecessary.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Computer systems generally have many dynamic (frequently changing) objects which intruders want to modify – and which a HIDS thus should monitor – but their dynamic nature makes them unsuitable for the checksum technique.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] To overcome this problem, HIDS employ various other detection techniques: monitoring changing file-attributes, log-files that decreased in size since last checked, and numerous other means to detect unusual events.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Reports can take the form of logs, e-mails or similar.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS will usually go to great lengths to prevent the object-database, checksum-database and its reports from any form of tampering.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] After all, if intruders succeed in modifying any of the objects the HIDS monitors, nothing can stop such intruders from modifying the HIDS itself – unless security administrators take appropriate precautions.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Many worms and viruses will try to disable anti-virus tools, for example.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Apart from crypto-techniques, HIDS might allow administrators to store the databases on a CD-ROM or on other read-only memory devices (another factor in favor of infrequent updates...) or storing them in some off-system memory.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Similarly, a HIDS will often send its logs off-system immediately – typically using VPN channels to some central management system.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One could argue that the trusted platform module comprises a type of HIDS.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Although its scope differs in many ways from that of a HIDS, fundamentally it provides a means to identify whether anything/anyone has tampered with a portion of a computer.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Architecturally this provides the ultimate (at least at this point in time) host-based intrusion detection, as depends on hardware external to the CPU itself, thus making it that much harder for an intruder to corrupt its object and checksum databases.
[src:osquery-endpoint/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] InfoWorld states that host-based intrusion-detection system software is a useful way for network managers to find malware, and suggest they run it on every server, not just critical servers.
[src:osquery-endpoint/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:osquery-endpoint/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:osquery-endpoint/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:osquery-endpoint/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:osquery-endpoint/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] The **envsys** framework is a kernel-level hardware monitoring sensors framework in NetBSD.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] Sensors are registered with the kernel through `**sysmon_envsys(9)**` API.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] The framework allows the user to amend the monitoring limits specified by the driver, and for the driver to perform monitoring of the sensors in kernel space, or even to programme a hardware chip to do the monitoring for the system automatically.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] Two levels of limits are defined: *critical* and *warning*, both of which additionally extend to an *over* and an *under* categorisation.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] If limit thresholds are crossed, a kernel event may be generated, which can be caught in the userland by `powerd` to execute a pre-defined user script.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] By comparison, in OpenBSD's hw.sensors, the monitoring of user-defined values is performed in userspace by `sensorsd`.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] However, the drivers for the most popular Super I/O chips like `lm(4)` and `itesio(4)` do not implement any fan control at all (in fact, historically, in all of OpenBSD, NetBSD and DragonFly, these drivers don't even report the duty cycle of the fans — only the actual RPM values are reported).
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] The framework undergone two major revisions: the first version of `envsys.h` was committed on 15 December 1999 (1999-12-15); with `envsys.4` man page following on 27 February 2000 (2000-02-27).
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] The serialisation with userland was reimplemented using property lists with the help of NetBSD's new proplib(3) library (the underlying transport layer between the kernel and userland still being done through ioctl).
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] The envsys framework was the precursor to OpenBSD's sysctl hw.sensors framework in 2003, and many drivers, as well as some sensor types, have been ported back and forth between NetBSD and OpenBSD.
[src:osquery-endpoint/sysmon] Support for sensors of `drive` type has been added to NetBSD on 1 May 2007, similar to `drive` type in OpenBSD, which was at the same time when bio(4) and bioctl were ported from OpenBSD to NetBSD.
